<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99920258737374></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99920258737374><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=6551&mid=99920258737374>RE: It isn't a spear...</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=6551&mid=99920258737374#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=89127><span id= >tdaelin</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>1 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 30th 4:16 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The naginata is in no way a "woman's" weapon, that's entirely a misconception.  It was an extremely common polearm, used by common bushi in battles through all of Japan's feudal period.  More than 150,000 men were involved in the Battle of Sekigahara, the conflict that unified Japan under Tokugawa.  You think all those men used swords?  Would you prefer to use a sword to repel charging cavalry or a polearm?  The naginata and yari were the backbone weapons on the army all through that Sengoku Jidai period.  Read and enjoy:<br><br><a href="http://members.aol.com/naginata/history.html" target=_new>http://members.aol.com/naginata/history.html</a><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
